How a wall of groovy lava lamps help encrypt the internet at the ðCloudflare Headquaters in San Francisco. 

If the site youâre visiting is encrypted by cybersecurity firm Cloudflare, your activity just might be protected by nothing other than a wall of lava lamps. The company has technology that monitors the lava lampsâ random movements and translates them into code that deters hackers from accessing almost 10% of international web traffic. You might think the lava lamps would be locked away for security, but the company actually welcomes the randomness that visitors bring to the code being generated. Visitors can check out the behind the scenes action (and play a part in internet security) at their SF headquarters at 101 Townsend St, San Francisco, CA 94107.

Stamps in Japan are everywhere and last time I visited I didn't have a notebook with me. This time we made it our aim to collect a stamp at every train station, attraction and cultural site that we could.

We came home with over 50 stamps!

So make sure to buy or carry a small notebook with you for fun and free momentos, we had so much fun trying to find the stamp at each station and we got some really special ones like Kawaguchiko Station which is the town we met at near Fuji 7 years ago and also the stamp for the park we got engaged in in Hokkaido.

They're all free and you can find them at all stations (except metro only stations). We also found them at major attractions such as Tokyo Tower, Sapporo Airport or Kyoto train museum.

Fusha Sakai, a member of Japanâs Osaka Public Universityâs Sakai Windmill Association, has made a big achievement in aviation. Theyâve created a special kind of aircraft that works like a bicycle. The Sakai Windmill Association is a group of students who work on making aircraft that are powered by people. They design, build, and fly their planes, even taking part in events like the Birdman Contest to try and set records.

Since they started in 1994, the Sakai Windmill Association has done more than 20 flights. Theyâve won six times in two different categories. Their newest creation is a flying bicycle, and it got a lot of attention when Massimo shared it on the social media platform X. The video got over 5.9 million views and 38,000 likes since it was first posted on November 8.

In the video, you can see someone pedaling the aircraft. It has wings and a big rotating fan, showing how Sakai is trying new ideas for manned flight. People have praised the invention, but some worry about getting tired from pedaling for a long time.

Even though theyâve faced problems, like having a damaged plane in last yearâs Birdman Contest, where they came 7th in the Human Powered Propeller Aircraft Division, the Sakai Windmill Association isnât giving up. Theyâre getting ready for this yearâs competition, aiming to show how creative and dedicated they are to pushing the limits of human-powered flight with their amazing flying bicycle.

(Save this reel before you forget)
Did you know that the Northern Lights are going to be stronger than the past two decades? 
Itâs not a clickbait, but the magic of a âsolar maximumâ bringing intense sun activity for the next couple of years and The Northern Lights, are closely tied to the sunâs activity hence making the next two years the best years to witness this phenomenon! 

If youâre planning to witness this cosmic dance, hereâs your ultimate guide!

ðï¸ Prime Viewing Months:
The Northern Lights illuminate the sky for a whopping 8 months, reaching their pinnacle during the Equinox effect in autumn and spring. Mark your calendars for September, October, March, and early April for the prime viewing months! Choose your months according to the place you are planning to visit because it can vary a bit.

ð Optimal Viewing Window:
Plan a week-long trip within the arctic circle, synced with the first or third quarter moon. This ensures the best weather conditions and a mesmerizing aurora spectacle.
